This is indeed quite funny, and it comes up (less impressively) a lot, so here's an entirely humorless response. ...

... The broad phenomenon here is arithmetical pseudo-proximity, which can easily seem like being toyed with. It's essentially illusory, though. Real arithmetical proximity is based on the Fundamental Theorem of Arithmetic. ...

... Best way to make this intuitively clear, and thus to shatter to the illusion, is through plexenomy. 
0 = 2
(0) =3 
00 = 4
((0)) = 5
You probably know how it works. Embedding escalates a number, by treating it as the index of a prime. The fifth prime being 11, it's (((0))) ...

... The plexenomy of 333 is ((0)00) (0) (0).
332: (((0) (0))) 00, so you see, not even close. 
666 is obviously closer: ((0)00) (0) (0) 0. ...
... Pseudo-arithmetical close hits are just playing with your head. Don't get distracted.
